Preheat your #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm wide wedges (no need to peel). Pop then onto a large #baking tray{}. Drizzle with @oil{drizzle}, season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, then toss to coat.

Spread out in a single layer. TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the middle shelf until golden, ~{30-40%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{60%g}.

Drain and rinse the @sweetcorn{150%g}(drained and rinsed) in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once the oil is hot, add the @British pork mince{240%g} and fry until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #spoon{} to break it up as it cooks, then drain and discard any excess fat.

Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince. The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Add the garlic and @Central American style spice mix{1%1%pot} to the pork. Cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @tomato puree{30%g}, @chicken stock paste{10%g}, sweetcorn and @water{50%ml}(for the sauce). Cook until piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Lay the @plain taco tortillas{4}(2 per person) onto a lightly oiled baking tray.

Spoon the pork and corn filling onto one half of each one. Top with the cheese.

Fold the other side over to make a semi-circle. Press down to keep together, then rub each with a little @oil{drizzle}.

When the wedges have about ~{15%minutes} left, bake the quesadillas onto the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{12-15%minutes}.

When the quesadillas are ready, remove them from the oven.

Carefully snip a small hole off the corner of the @mayonnaise{32%g} sachet and pipe a spider web shape onto each quesadilla. Get any little devils with you involved in the fun!

Serve the wedges alongside with a dollop of @tomato ketchup{2%tbsp} for dipping.

Enjoy!